  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "Molecular Pathogenesis",
      "content": "The molecular pathogenesis of SBA involves distinct genomic alterations that differentiate it from colorectal and gastroesophageal cancers. Key driver mutations include KRAS and TP53, which are frequent in both SBA and CRC. However, APC mutations are significantly less common in SBA compared to CRC (27% in SBA vs. 76% in CRC; P < .001), suggesting a unique neoplastic transformation pathway [10]. Genomic profiling has identified that SMAD4 and CDKN2A mutations are more common in SBA than in gastroesophageal cancers or CRC [10]. While BRAF mutations occur at a rate similar to CRC, only 10% of BRAF-mutant SBAs have a V600E alteration, compared to >70% in BRAF-mutant CRC [10]. Importantly, biomarkers relevant to targeted and immunotherapeutic treatments are enriched in SBA compared to CRC. These include a higher incidence of MSI-H/dMMR, higher rates of programmed death-ligand 1 (PD-L1) expression, and higher tumor mutational burden-high (TMB-H). One study reported that 9.5% of SBA samples had a TMB of >20 mut/Mb compared to 4.3% in CRC (P = .001) [10, 18, 19]. Human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 (HER2) alterations, RET fusions, NTRK 1/2/3 fusions, and KRAS G12C mutations are also actionable targets identified in SBA [14, 20, 21]. The presence of these alterations provides the rationale for a biomarker-driven approach to systemic therapy, including the use of checkpoint inhibitors for dMMR/MSI-H or ultra-hypermutated tumors, and targeted therapies for specific mutations."
    }
